* [ ] 1 ) Write the calculator program using function pointers.

* [ ] 2 ) Write the calculator program using array of function pointers.

* [ ] 3 ) Write the calculator program using a function that accepts a function pointer as argument and invokes it.
eg., fptr = ADD;
invokeptr(fptr);

invokeptr(int (*fptr) (int,int))
{
printf("%d\n",fptr(3,4));
}

* [ ] 4 ) Complete the below program :
int x; int y;
int * const ptr = &x;

we cannot modify ptr to point to a different address using ptr directly. Do it indirectly.

* [ ] 5 ) Complete the below program :
const int x=10;  
const int * ptr=&x;  
ptr = &x;

x value cannot be changed using x or *ptr. Do it indirectly.

* [ ] 6 ) Complete the below program :

const int x = 10;
const int y = 10;
const int * const ptr = &x;
int **pptr = &ptr;

modify the value of x,y , and ptr (to point to y). You can only create one extra pointer variable.
